### 3.3 Spring Cloud

> [!info] What it is
> Spring Cloud is a set of tools built on Spring Boot for building microservices systems. Provides service discovery, config management, load balancing, circuit breakers, gateways.

#### 3.3.1 Spring Cloud Gateway

> [!info] What it is
> An API Gateway built on Spring WebFlux. Single entry point for all client requests, routes to appropriate microservices, applies cross-cutting concerns (auth, rate limiting, logging).

**Why used in AcquirerX:**
- Hides microservice complexity from clients
- Centralized authentication (JWT validation)
- Request routing based on path or headers
- Load balancing across service instances
- Rate limiting per client/endpoint

**Key Gateway concepts:**
- **Routes** — define which incoming request goes to which service
- **Predicates** — conditions for routes (path, header, method)
- **Filters** — pre/post processing (auth, logging, request modification)

**Interview prep:**
- *"Why an API Gateway?"* → Centralizes cross-cutting concerns, hides internal architecture, simplifies client code, enables A/B testing and canary releases
- *"What's the difference between Gateway and Load Balancer?"* → Load balancer just distributes traffic; Gateway adds intelligence (auth, routing logic, transformations)

#### 3.3.2 Eureka (Service Discovery)

> [!info] What it is
> A service registry. Microservices register themselves with Eureka on startup. Other services query Eureka to find healthy instances.

**Why service discovery matters:**
- Microservice IPs/ports change dynamically (containers, autoscaling)
- Hardcoding addresses doesn't work
- Eureka provides a "phone book" — services register, others look up

**How it works:**
1. Service starts → registers with Eureka server (name, host, port, health URL)
2. Eureka stores this registry
3. Sends heartbeats every 30 seconds to stay registered
4. Other services query Eureka by service name → get instance list
5. Client-side load balancing picks an instance

**Interview prep:**
- *"What if Eureka itself goes down?"* → Each service caches the registry locally, can continue routing for a while. Eureka clusters are deployed for HA
- *"Eureka vs Consul vs Zookeeper?"* → All are service discovery tools. Eureka is Netflix's, designed for AWS. Consul (HashiCorp) adds KV store + health checks. Zookeeper is older, stronger consistency

#### 3.3.3 OpenFeign

> [!info] What it is
> A declarative REST client. You define an interface with annotations; Feign auto-generates the implementation. Makes calling other microservices feel like calling local methods.

**Why used in AcquirerX:**
- Cleaner than RestTemplate (less boilerplate)
- Integrates with Eureka for service discovery
- Supports load balancing (with Ribbon/Spring Cloud LoadBalancer)
- Can chain with Resilience4J for circuit breaking

**Example pattern:**
```java
@FeignClient(name = "merchant-service")
public interface MerchantClient {
    @GetMapping("/merchants/{id}")
    Merchant getMerchant(@PathVariable Long id);
}
```

Spring auto-implements this interface, looks up `merchant-service` in Eureka, and calls it.

**Interview prep:**
- *"Feign vs RestTemplate vs WebClient?"* → Feign is declarative (interface-based); RestTemplate is imperative (sync); WebClient is reactive (async)
- *"How does Feign integrate with Eureka?"* → Service name (not URL) is used; Feign resolves it via Eureka at runtime

#### 3.3.4 Resilience4J

> [!info] What it is
> A lightweight fault tolerance library inspired by Netflix Hystrix. Provides circuit breakers, retries, rate limiters, bulkheads, time limiters.

**Why used in AcquirerX:**
- Microservices fail — handle it gracefully
- Prevent cascading failures
- Implement graceful degradation
- Critical for payment systems (one slow service shouldn't kill the whole chain)

**Key patterns:**

**Circuit Breaker:**
- States: CLOSED (normal) → OPEN (failing) → HALF_OPEN (testing recovery)
- After N failures, circuit opens — fail fast without trying
- After timeout, half-opens — let one request through
- If it succeeds, closes again

**Retry:**
- Auto-retry failed calls with backoff
- Use for transient failures (network blips)

**Bulkhead:**
- Limit concurrent calls to a service
- Prevents one slow dependency from exhausting threads

**Rate Limiter:**
- Cap requests per time window
- Protects against abuse

**Interview prep:**
- *"Walk me through circuit breaker states"* → CLOSED accepts traffic; on threshold failures it goes OPEN (rejects immediately); after wait time, HALF_OPEN tests one request — success → CLOSED, failure → OPEN
- *"Why not use Hystrix?"* → Hystrix is in maintenance mode. Resilience4J is the modern replacement — lightweight, functional, no servlet dependency

