### 3.4 JPA + Hibernate

> [!info] What JPA is
> Java Persistence API — a specification for ORM (Object-Relational Mapping) in Java. Lets you map Java objects to database tables.

> [!info] What Hibernate is
> The most popular JPA implementation. Translates JPA annotations into SQL.

**Why JPA in AcquirerX:**
- Maps 27 Java entities to database tables automatically
- No manual SQL for basic CRUD
- Supports complex relationships (one-to-many, many-to-many)
- Caching (first-level and second-level)
- Lazy loading for performance

**Key JPA annotations:**
- `@Entity` — marks a class as a database entity
- `@Table` — specifies table name
- `@Id` — primary key
- `@GeneratedValue` — auto-generated ID
- `@Column` — column properties
- `@OneToMany`, `@ManyToOne` — relationships
- `@JoinColumn` — foreign key column

**Spring Data JPA:**
- Builds on top of JPA
- Provides `JpaRepository` interface with CRUD methods out of the box
- Auto-generates queries from method names: `findByEmailAndStatus(...)`

**Interview prep:**
- *"What is the N+1 problem?"* → When you fetch N entities and lazy-load a relationship → triggers N additional queries. Solution: JOIN FETCH or @EntityGraph
- *"Lazy vs Eager loading?"* → Lazy: relationships fetched only when accessed. Eager: fetched immediately. Lazy is the default and usually preferred
- *"What is @Transactional?"* → Wraps the method in a database transaction. Rolls back on RuntimeException by default
- *"JPQL vs Native SQL?"* → JPQL is object-oriented (queries entities), database-agnostic. Native SQL is database-specific but more powerful

