### 3.8 MDC Logging (Mapped Diagnostic Context)

> [!info] What MDC is
> A logging feature that lets you attach context (user ID, request ID, trace ID) to all log statements in a thread. Makes distributed tracing possible.

**Why used in AcquirerX:**
- Multiple microservices handle a single payment
- Need to trace a transaction across all services
- Each request gets a unique `traceId` added to MDC
- All log statements automatically include the traceId

**How it works:**
1. Gateway/filter receives request → generates trace ID
2. Stores it in MDC: `MDC.put("traceId", uuid)`
3. Logger picks up MDC context automatically
4. Trace ID is propagated to downstream services (via headers)
5. Each service logs with the same trace ID
6. Searching logs by trace ID reconstructs the full request journey

**Interview prep:**
- *"How does distributed tracing work?"* → Each request gets a trace ID at entry point. Propagated to all services via headers (e.g., X-Trace-Id). All logs include trace ID. Tools like Zipkin/Jaeger visualize the trace
- *"MDC vs Spring Sleuth vs OpenTelemetry?"* → MDC is a logging library feature. Spring Sleuth adds trace IDs automatically. OpenTelemetry is the modern unified standard

