## 🎤 PART 5 — Common Interview Questions

### Q1: Walk me through AcquirerX end-to-end (2 minutes)

> AcquirerX is a Merchant Acquiring and POS Switch platform I architected during my Cognizant internship. It handles the full payment lifecycle for merchant transactions — from onboarding merchants, provisioning POS terminals, switching live transactions between acquirers and card networks, settling funds, reconciling records, and managing disputes.
>
> The system is built as 12 microservices in Spring Boot 3.x, each owning a domain — merchant, terminal, switch, settlement, reconciliation, dispute, and so on. They communicate through OpenFeign REST clients with Resilience4J circuit breakers for fault tolerance. Eureka handles service discovery, and Spring Cloud Gateway is the single entry point for the React frontend.
>
> Data persistence is via Spring Data JPA with Hibernate over 27 entities. The platform implements production-grade patterns — JWT-based RBAC, dynamic JPQL filtering with pagination, PAN masking for PCI compliance, MDC-based distributed logging, and Swagger documentation for all services. Spring Actuator endpoints expose health and metrics for observability.

### Q2: Why microservices over monolith?

> A few reasons. First, domain boundaries map naturally — merchant onboarding, switching, settlement are independent business processes that evolve at different rates. Second, fault isolation — if the dispute service crashes, transactions keep flowing. Third, independent scaling — switching is high-throughput and needs more instances than dispute. Fourth, team scalability — different teams could own different services. The tradeoff is operational complexity — debugging across services, network failures, eventual consistency. But for a system at this scale, the benefits outweigh the costs.

### Q3: Walk me through a Resilience4J circuit breaker

> Three states. CLOSED is the normal state — requests pass through. If failures exceed a threshold (say 50% of last 20 calls), it transitions to OPEN — all requests fail immediately without hitting the downstream service. This prevents cascading failures. After a timeout (say 30 seconds), it goes HALF_OPEN — lets one or a few requests through to test recovery. If they succeed, it closes again. If they fail, it stays open. We used circuit breakers around every inter-service Feign call, especially around the settlement and switching services where downstream failures would otherwise propagate.

### Q4: How does JWT-based RBAC work in your system?

> User logs in via the auth service — credentials are validated, and a JWT is issued containing the user ID, role, and expiry. The JWT is signed with a secret key using HMAC SHA-256. The client stores the token and includes it in every API request via the Authorization header. Spring Cloud Gateway intercepts every request, validates the JWT signature, checks expiry, and propagates the token downstream. Each microservice extracts the role from the JWT and enforces RBAC using Spring Security's @PreAuthorize annotations. For example, only users with the ADMIN role can call merchant onboarding APIs.

### Q5: How does Eureka service discovery work?

> Eureka has two parts — the Eureka server and Eureka clients. On startup, each microservice registers with the Eureka server, providing its service name, host, port, and health check URL. The Eureka server maintains the registry. Other services query the registry by service name to find healthy instances. Heartbeats are sent every 30 seconds to keep the registration alive. If heartbeats stop, the instance is evicted after a timeout. When OpenFeign makes a call to "merchant-service", it asks Eureka for an instance, then makes the actual HTTP call. This decouples services from hardcoded IPs and ports, which is critical when running in containers where addresses change.

### Q6: What is the N+1 problem and how did you solve it?

> The N+1 problem happens when you load N entities, and then for each entity you trigger an additional query to fetch a related entity. So one query becomes N+1 queries. Classic example — loading all merchants and then accessing their terminals collection lazily — that triggers a query per merchant. We solved it with JOIN FETCH in JPQL or @EntityGraph annotations, which fetch the related collection in a single join query. For collections where this isn't practical, we used batch fetching with @BatchSize to fetch related entities in batches of, say, 20 at a time.

### Q7: How did you handle distributed tracing across services?

> We used MDC — Mapped Diagnostic Context — in our logging. When a request enters the gateway, we generate a UUID and put it in the MDC as a "traceId". This trace ID is propagated via HTTP headers to downstream services. Each service extracts it from the header and re-adds it to its MDC. The logging configuration includes the trace ID in every log line. So when debugging an issue, we can search logs across all services for the trace ID and reconstruct the full request flow.

### Q8: Why JWT instead of sessions?

> JWT is stateless. With sessions, you need a centralized session store (Redis, sticky sessions) — which becomes a bottleneck and a failure point in microservices. JWT carries the user's identity and claims inside the token itself, signed for tamper-proofness. Every service can validate independently without a network call. This works perfectly with horizontal scaling and microservices where requests can land on any instance. The tradeoff is you can't easily invalidate a JWT mid-flight — for that, we use short expiry (15-30 min) plus refresh tokens, or a Redis-backed blacklist for high-security cases.

### Q9: What's the biggest challenge you faced?

> Coordinating data consistency across services for settlement workflows. A settlement touches the switch service (which has the original transaction), the settlement service (which moves money), the reconciliation service (which records the match), and the notification service. You can't use a database transaction across services. We implemented a saga pattern where each step emits events, and if a downstream step fails, compensating transactions undo the previous steps. Getting the ordering and error handling right was non-trivial. We also added idempotency keys so retried operations don't duplicate effects.

### Q10: How would you scale AcquirerX further?

> A few areas. First, observability — add Prometheus + Grafana for metrics, Loki for logs, Jaeger for distributed tracing. Second, async messaging — introduce Kafka for high-throughput transaction flows; currently they're sync REST which can bottleneck. Third, caching — add Redis for hot data like merchant profiles. Fourth, database scaling — read replicas for reporting workloads, partitioning transactions by date or merchant. Fifth, deployment — containerize with Docker, orchestrate with Kubernetes, add CI/CD via GitHub Actions. Sixth, security hardening — move secrets to Vault, add mutual TLS between services. Finally, performance testing — load test critical paths like transaction switching to find bottlenecks.

### Q11: Why Spring Boot 3 over Spring Boot 2?

> Spring Boot 3 requires Java 17+, which gives us modern language features like records, sealed classes, and pattern matching. It uses Jakarta EE namespaces instead of javax, which is the long-term direction. It adds native image support via GraalVM, which can dramatically reduce startup time and memory footprint — important for serverless and Kubernetes. It also has updated security defaults and observability improvements.

### Q12: What is dynamic JPQL filtering?

> Letting users filter results by any combination of fields without writing dozens of specific repository methods. For example, on the merchant search endpoint, users might filter by status, region, MCC code, and date range. We used JPA Specifications — composable predicates — to build the query dynamically based on which filters are non-null. Each filter becomes a Specification, and we combine them with .and() or .or(). The result is paginated using a Pageable parameter so we return a Page object with content + total count.

